  "prompt": "What is the order of colors in the rainbow? Why do they appear in that order?",
  "response": "The order of colors in a rainbow is typically remembered by the acronym \"ROYGBIV,\" which stands for:\n\n- Red\n- Orange\n- Yellow\n- Green\n- Blue\n- Indigo\n- Violet\n\nRainbows appear in this order due to the process of dispersion, which occurs when sunlight passes through water droplets in the atmosphere. When light enters a droplet, it slows down and bends (refraction). Different wavelengths (or colors) of light bend at slightly different angles. As a result, when the light exits the droplet, it spreads out into a spectrum of colors.\n\nSpecifically, red light bends the least while violet light bends the most. Because of this variation in bending, the colors separate and spread out in the order of their wavelengths, resulting in the distinct bands of color that we see in a rainbow.",
